title: Upgrade Race Clinic
description:
$49.99 for WSBA members, $74.99 for non-members
 
Start your season on the right track. Our USA Cycling-sanctioned upgrade clinic teaches new racers the fundamentals with hands-on practice and feedback from experienced coaches. This class accelerates the learning curve for new racers by offering riders who complete the class three mass start points (for Cat 5 men) or three upgrade points (for Cat 4 men and women) toward their next upgrade. 
Road 401 is held on several dates in February and March. The class covers skills required in racing: pack riding; tactics; cornering & handling; etiquette, and more. It also covers types of racing and USAC rules. The class starts and finishes at our Sand Point shop. Bring your bike, warm riding clothes, and a snack. We start with a classroom presentation on the technical elements of racing, head out for two hours of handling drills, and conclude with a short written test.

Please bring proof of WSBA membership and know your USA Cycling license number.

title: Team Group Health Independence Valley Road Race
The Ridge Circuit Race and TT
Ronde Ohop (Vintage)
description: The 2015 Ronde Ohop is the 11th edition of the race. In celebration we are using the original course and the race will be a true NW Kermesse with multiple laps of the Mashel Loop. The Ronde Ohop is part of the 2015 NW Kermesse Series of races that mix paved and unpaved roads to evoke the Belgian tradition of cobbled, short, fast and hard races.
course: Registration and finish are at the Mashel Loop field. Race starts at the North Park Entrance. Races will run counter clockwise laps of the Mashel-Nisqually loop. The Mashel-Nisqually Loop is 1 miles of paved road & 1 miles of dirt road per lap and includes the 50 meter Mur de Mashel each lap.
registration: Online at USACycling.org or day of at the Mashel Loop. Registration closes 40 minutes before the start of each event. The entry fee includes $3 per rider per day for USA Cycling insurance. A current year USA Cycling Rider Waiver and Release form must be signed by the participant and, if under 18, by the parent or legal guardian. WSBA numbers will be used. The officials request that both bib numbers be clearly visible placed parallel with your jersey’s side seam on the back and above the pockets. Frame number should be attached per WSBA instructions. Examples of proper placement: http://gcracingllc.com/numberplacement.aspx. Rental numbers are available for a $10 fee ($5 refundable). For out-of-state riders a $5 number refundable deposit will be assessed.
notes: Neutral wheel support will be provided. I However wheels will be limited and two addition wheel-in/wheels-out pits will be marked on the course for a total of three wheel pits on the Mashel Loop. Riders are highly encourage to bring spare wheels. The organizer is not responsible for wheels or equipment left at the race. Upgrade, Ranking & Series Points: Upgrade points: Cat 4/5s will receive upgrade points based on the road race points schedule. Full stop. Cat 1/2/3 Race: Cat 3 riders will receive upgrade points based on the road race points schedule for their placing relative to other Cat 3s. This means if you get 5th in the 1/2/3 race but are the 1st placed Cat 3 you get points for a 1st Place finish. Cat 1 / 2 riders will receive upgrade points based on the Criterium points schedule for their overall placing. This means if you get 5th in the 1/2/3 race but are the 1st placed Cat 2 you get points for a 5th Place finish. Scoring: Masters and Women’s start together but are scored separately. Masters races will have an overall winner as well as separate scoring for 35+ 1-2-3, 50+ and 35+ 4-5 groups for USACycling Ranking points. Promoter may separate fields if size warrants. Series Points: Series points will be for the Cat 1/2/3 Race, Masters Overall (1-5) and Women’s fields. Series winner will receive a winner’s jersey and free entry into 2015 series events. The gift certs are $5-35.
directions: Parking will be at the Nisqually- Mashel State Park next to 437th St E & Medical Springs Rd under the power lines. From North or South on I-5 Take exit 127. Drive east on Hwy 512 for two miles, then take the Pacific Ave./Mt. Rainier exit south. Follow Pacific Ave. about five miles to where the road splits in a "Y." Follow signs for Mt. Rainier (the left branch of the fork) taking Hwy 7 south. Drive about 17 miles, passing Ohop Valley Rd. At the top of the long sweeping hill turn right onto the Mashel Prairie Road on the right side. Go about ¾ of a mile and park on the right side under the power lines.

title: Friday Night Racing at Marymoor Velodrome
Tour de Bloom Omnium
description:
Tour de Bloom Omnium is a two-day event in the Greater Wenatchee Area that includes 3 stages. It is held during the community's Apple Blossom Festival. The Hill Climb is conducted between Squilchuck State Park and Mission Ridge Ski & Board Resort. The Criterium takes place in historic downtown Wenatchee. And the Road Race unfolds among the rolling wheat fields near Waterville. 

An omnium is a multi-stage race where participants can earn points in each race that will count towards the overall placement.
course:
The Hill Climb features one of the more unique courses in the Pacific Northwest — a climb of 1,850 vertical feet over 4.25 miles, ending at the Mission Ridge ski resort in the Wenatchee National Forest. Along the way, riders will encounter several technical turns. 

The Criterium takes place in the heart of historic downtown Wenatchee over a six-block loop. The start and finish is on Wenatchee Avenue, between Palouse and First streets. 

The Road Race incorporates roads located in the classic Waterville wheat country. The course is flat with rollers.
registration:
Register via USA Cycling or at https://www.usacycling.org/register/2015-440 

Here is the fee schedule: 

Early bird (Jan. 15 through March 31) 

Masters and seniors — Individual race: $32.52; Omnium: $86.72 

Juniors — Individual race: $18.43; Omnium: $48.78 

Regular (April 1 through April 30) 

Masters and seniors — Individual race: $37.94; Omnium: $97.56 

Juniors — Individual race: $21.68; Omnium: $54.20 

Day of (May 2 and May 3) 

Masters and seniors — Individual race: $43.36; Omnium: $108.40 

Juniors — Individual race: $24.93; Omnium: $59.62
notes:
Race headquarters is located at Arlberg Sports, Grand Central Building, 25 N. Wenatchee Ave., Wenatchee, WA 98801

Rider’s license will be checked prior to picking up race packets, bib numbers, and other information. Everyone is required to check in at packet pickup and sign the USA Cycling Competitive Release Form. All juniors must have their parent sign a USAC release form before they will be permitted to race. One day licenses will be available at packet pickup for Cat 4 women and Cat 5 men. All international riders with a UCI license from another National Federation will be permitted to race. All racers must initial that they have read the tech guide.

For more info — including race categories, parking and lodging — visit www.tourdebloom.com
directions:
Wenatchee is located in central Washington state, approximately 2.5 hours by vehicle from both Seattle and Spokane, and 5 hours by vehicle from both Portland and Vancouver, B.C.

Wenatchee also is served by Horizon Air, a subsidiary of Alaska Airlines.

For directions to each race stage, check out the tech guide at www.tourdebloom.com

title: Sumner Buckley Kermesse
description: The Sumner Buckley is a 2015 Northwest Kermesse Series event. The Northwest Kermesse series of events evoke the mythical races described by juniors cyclists returning from Belgium. Northwest Kermesse races feature a balance of paved and dirt road and reward riders that display tenacity.
course: Race starts and finishes on Radke Rd and will run clockwise. The course is flat and approximately 3.9 miles in length with 1.4 miles dirt and 2.5 miles paved road.
registration: $30 online USACycling.org or $35 day of at Maris Farm. Registration closes 20 minutes before the start of each event. The entry fee includes $3 per rider per day for USA Cycling insurance. A current year USA Cycling Rider Waiver and Release form must be signed by the participant and, if under 18, by the parent or legal guardian.
notes: While Kermesse races are hard, they are also accessible to new and novice riders. The dirt section are not technical and unlike regular road races riders that are dropped are able to continue to fight to the finish and it is common to see riders catch groups ahead of them. Either road or cyclocross bikes can be used but 25 - 28c tires are highly recommended. Neutral wheel pits will be available on the course. C Race: Cat 4/5s will receive upgrade points based on the road race points schedule. Full stop. B Races: Cat 3 riders will receive upgrade points based on the road race points schedule for their placing relative to other Cat 3s. This means if you get 5th in the 1/2/3 race but are the 1st placed Cat 3 you get points for a 1st Place finish. A Race: Cat 1 / 2 riders will receive upgrade points based on the Criterium points schedule for their overall placing. This means if you get 5thin the 1/2/3 race but are the 1st placed Cat 2 you get points for a 5thPlace finish. Scoring: Masters and Women’s start together but are scored separately. Masters races will have an overall winner as well as separate scoring for 1-2-3 and 4-5 groups for USACycling Ranking points. Promoter may separate fields if size warrants. Series Points: Series points will be for the Cat 1/2/3 Race, Masters Overall (1-5) and Women’s fields. Series winner will receive a winner’s jersey and free entry into 2016 series events.
directions: Main parking, registration and staging will be at the Take Root Farm in Buckley. Address is: 22416 Buckley Tapps Hwy E, Buckley, WA 98321. • Overflow Parking will be on 246th Ave East, Buckley WA (this is a dead end road opposite Maris Farms).

notes: While Kermesse races are hard, they are also accessible to new and novice riders. title: Sumner Buckley Kermesse p/b Machete Squad
description: The Buckley Slough Kermesse is NW Kermesse event mixing paved & gravel road for an experience reminiscent of the hyperbolic description of Belgian races. NW Kermesse races are hard but accessible to all levels and reward riders that display tenacity.
course: Race starts and finishes on Barkubine / Radke Rd and will run clockwise. The course is flat and approximately 3.9 miles in length with 1.4 miles gravel (Pipeline Trail) and 2.5 miles paved road (Barkubine/Radke/Tapps-Buckley).  The gravel section, named Resistant Passage, has deep gravel and will sap rider energy.  Riders are advised to use tires that are tear/cut resistant to avoid flats.
registration: $20 ($10 early bird registration) online USACycling.org.   Pre-registration only.  Due to county permit restrictions field sizes are capped at 25 riders.  Registration closes 8pm the Friday before the event.  The entry fee includes $3 per rider per day for USA Cycling insurance.  Day of Licences can be purchased online when registering.  A current year USA Cycling Rider Waiver and Release form must be signed by the participant and, if under 18, by the parent or legal guardian.
notes: The Buckley Slough Kermesse will be using a point-per-lap & regroup format.  This format is designed to ensure that the event is both challenging and accessible to new and novice riders.  Format description:   The top 3 riders on each lap will receive time bonuses.  These bonuses will be deducted from the overall time assigned based on the pack's time over the entire event.  At the end of each lap the race will neutralize and the pack will regroup.   Dropped riders will sit out a lap and then rejoin on the next regroup.  Dropped riders will be assessed a time penalty based on each lap missed.  This is specifically intended to allow riders who might otherwise be dropped from the event the opportunity to rejoin the race and get their "gravel legs".  The cut-off for whether a rider is dropped each lap will be at the officials discretion.  The dirt section is not technical.   Either road or cyclocross bikes can be used but a minimum of 28c *tear resistant* tires are highly recommended.  Riders may place spare wheels on the course.  There will be no official wheel pits.  Upgrade points:  Cat 4/5s will receive upgrade points based on the road race points schedule. Full stop.  Cat 3 riders will receive upgrade points based on the road race points schedule for their placing relative to other Cat 3s.  This means if you get 5th in the 1/2/3 race but are the 1st placed Cat 3 you get points for a 1st Place finish.  Cat 1 / 2 riders will receive upgrade points based on the Criterium points schedule for their overall placing. This means if you get 5th in the 1/2/3 race but are the 1st placed Cat 2 you get points for a 5th Place finish.   Kermesse Series points will be for the Cat 1/2/3 Race, Masters Overall (1-5) and Women’s fields.  Series winner will receive a winner’s jersey and free entry into 2016 series events.
directions: Main parking, registration and staging will be on 258th Ave E south of Sumner Buckley Hwy, Buckley WA (the road is about 1 mile long total).  Overflow parking will be available on the Pipeline Trail west of the race course.  Do not park south of the trail entrance.
